# Port-Forwarding and Tunneling - {{ workspace.display_name }}

This guide documents the hybrid local development workflow where a local component connects directly to remote dependencies (e.g. databases, queues) hosted in DEV/SIT Kubernetes clusters or cloud networks.

---

## State & Runtime Directory

The port forwarding scripts manage background tunnel state cleanly using an ignored runtime directory:
- State location: **`.runtime/port-forwarding/`** (This directory is explicitly added to `.gitignore` to prevent tracking runtime state).
- Tunnel files: Stored as `.pid` files containing the system process IDs of active tunnels.

---

## Command Controls

### 1. Initialize Tunnels
Spin up background tunnels to remote cloud resources for the selected environment (defaults to `DEV`):
```bash
./scripts/start-port-forwarding.sh DEV
```
This runs the mapping scripts, saves active tunnel PIDs into `.runtime/port-forwarding/`, and prepares local ports.

### 2. Check Tunnel Health
List the status of active tunnels:
```bash
./scripts/status-port-forwarding.sh
```

### 3. Terminate Tunnels
Shutdown background processes and clean up the runtime directory:
```bash
./scripts/stop-port-forwarding.sh
```

---

## Scaling to Kubernetes

In the first version, these scripts output mock state handles. In future milestones, replace mock commands inside `./scripts/start-port-forwarding.sh` with actual network bindings, e.g.:
```bash
kubectl port-forward svc/students-service 8081:8081 -n dev & echo $! > .runtime/port-forwarding/students-service.pid
```
This keeps operational procedures identical while scaling into cloud-native clusters.
